    Bu kitobim.

title: -imiz

title: -ingiz
contenthtml:

    "This is your book."

title: -niki
contenthtml:
Suffix

-niki (-ники)

  1. Shows that an item is the possession of the noun before niki. Similar to stand alone possessive pronouns "mine", "yours", "its" etc.
    • Bu sizniki.
      "This is yours."

Usage notes

When attached to the first person singular pronoun, "men", the form is "meniki."

title: -ning
contenthtml:
Suffix

-ning (Cyrillic spelling -нинг)

  1. Genitive case marker. Indicates that either that previous word has possession of the following word, or the following word is an attribute or a portion of the previous word. It functions like the English suffix “'s”.
    • Otamning ruchkasi.
      It's my father's pen.

Usage notes

The first person singular pronoun men and the second person singular pronoun sen are formed as "mening", and "sening" respectively.

title: da
contenthtml:
Particle

da (Cyrillic spelling да)

  1. Locative case marker. It is used to show the time or the place of an action. Equates to "in", or "at" in English.
    • Samarqandda yashayman.
      I live in Samarqand.
    • Soat uchda boraman.
      I go at 3 o'clock.

Usage notes

  • When used after interrogative pronouns da can take on different meanings. Pronouns such as kim (“who”), nima (“what”), qayer (“where”), necha (“how many, how much”) become kimda (“to whom”), nimada (“with what, by using what”), qayerda (“from where”), nechada (“what time”).
